snippet.textDisplay: The flat wine bottle seems to be more of a gimmick than anything, since we've already solved this problem. Boxed wine is already shipped in cardboard that's way more efficient use of space than that box, and the recyclable inner bags likewise. The packaging on those is extremely space-efficient, and they actually pass that on to the buyer - you get twice the volume per price for similarly good wine. Plus it keeps longer, since dispensing it doesn't expose the wine to air.
snippet.textOriginal: The flat wine bottle seems to be more of a gimmick than anything, since we've already solved this problem. snippet.textDisplay: That wine bottle is supposedly so eco friendly, but it is a small fix that doesn't fix a larger issue. In Germany there is a small fee on different bottle types and by returning them you get the money back. Glass melting uses up a lot of energy, but is way better reusalbe (by washing the bottles) or recyclable. We reuse most glass bottles up to 50 times and the recycling rate is 89%. How about that. PET is depending on the way it is made wayy less recyclable. So it's life cycle probably ends at 2 usages (just guessing) because of coatings, degradation in the recyling process and more. Also shipping packages is shit for the environment anyway

snippet.textDisplay:
Is it just perception? Alcohol is super reactive -- it seems reasonable to make the claim that glass is a substantially better vessel for wine. (Caveat being I am not a scientist, lol.) I mean, plastic bottles of pop taste significantly different than when it comes from glass bottles or even aluminum cans.

Also -- I will say, the flat packaging is cool, and that is significant for environmental impact. And the plastic can be good, as Barry said, for people with small kids. But it's worth pointing out that reusing glass bottles is much better for the environment than recycling plastic. What would be really cool is if we could make good, strong glass bottles in that shape and establish a program for their reuse -- it may not be as good of a solution for Barry's kid, but recycling plastic is pretty significantly worse for the environment than using a substance that doesn't need to be re-proccessed a second time. We'd have to establish the infrastructure to reuse the glass bottles, though, which is the biggest problem.

Hope this doesn't come off as attacking the company or sorted -- I think this is really cool and innovative! I just think in terms of environmental impact, it functions better as a great idea to push us in the right direction than an environmentally friendly end product.

snippet.textDisplay:
Singaporean here! Instead of eating the watermelon seeds whole, we eat the watermelon seeds like so:
Step 1: Pick up ONE seed xD
Step 2: Place the seed anywhere between your teeth (you can use your front teeth, your molars, anything goes), the thinner edges of the seed should be against your teeth instead of the flat sides (Hope you know what I mean)
Step 3: Bite down slowly until you reach the right pressure to crack the seed in half (it will probably take you several attempts to find the right amount of pressure to use)
Step 4: Once cracked, use your fingers to peel open the seed which should now be in 2 flat halves with an inner seed on 1 side.
Step 5: Savour the treasure inside that is the inner seed.
Step 6: Discard the seed shells
Sounds like alot of work for a single seed but practise often and you will be cracking in no time!
FYI experts like my mom are able to crack and eat the inner seed without even peeling them with their fingers. Let's see if you guys can figure out how to do that :D
